1.58pm Right then. Lovely sunny afternoon. Stephen Cook will face the new pink ball. Three slips for Mitch Starc. Off we go then.

1.41pm Here's some trivia. This is the first time since the 1981 Ashes series in England that Australia have given Test caps to five players, in a series. Also, Firdose tells me Jimmy Cook faced the first delivery for SA in white-ball cricket back in 1992. Stephen Cook may face the first pink-ball delivery in 2016.

Nathan Pringle: "Tempering expectations, but excited to see the new look batting line-up. Looking forwards, would like to think they find a starting place for Shaun Marsh once he's back fit. Quality player."

Shailesh: "Nikhil, SA will be possibly bowling fourth innings; do you think having a wrist spinner in the form of Shamshi will come handy (looking at the pitch)?" Possible, but may have to play the support role through the Test.

Jk: "I also remember that Jimmy Cook played SA's first ball after readmission into test cricket in Durban in 92. Unfortunately for him, he was dismissed caught at slip off Kapil Dev"

Kaushal: "Hopefully, this is a start of a new era for Australia. David Warner with his opening partner who can do a Cowan, Smith and Handscomb in the middle, Wade/Nevill (hopefully he's not discarded) and Maddinson in the lower middle and the perennially competitive bowlers. "

1.30pm Du Plessis wins the toss and South Africa opt to bat

Tabraiz Shamsi is making his Test debut too, he comes in for Keshav Maharaj.

"I'm just glad that I can play some cricket and hopefully extend that lead of ours," says Faf. "It was absolutely amazing. A great spectacle. Slightly less grass than last year, the ball has changed a bit so might not do as much," says Steven Smith.

Renshaw was handed his cap by Ian Healy, Handscomb by Chris Rogers and Maddinson by Simon Katich.

Mal: "Smith last won the toss in February 2016, in NZ. He has lost every toss since the tour to Sri Lanka. Time for a new tossing coach?"

1.20pm The toss isn't far away. Not sure what I'd be doing actually. Australia has confirmed their XI: David Warner, Matt Renshaw, Usman Khawaja, Steven Smith (capt), Peter Handscomb, Nic Maddinson, Matthew Wade (wk), Mitchell Starc, Josh Hazlewood, Nathan Lyon, Jackson Bird.

1.10pm In the South African camp, the mood is not as boisterous as it should be, they've already beaten one of the best away. And here's why. A reminder that Faf du Plessis was found guilty of ball-tampering, but is allowed to play this game. All those years back, it began here for Faf.

Law 42.3: "polishing the ball provided that no artificial substance is used," has its problems and Firdose Moonda explains why.

Nathan: "Still baffled how Cameron White wasn't picked but nonetheless looking forward to today" Looking ahead to the future probably?

1.00pm An extraordinary sequence of events has panned out over the past few days/weeks. A lot has gone on, a lot said, a lot not said. Finally, it is now time to put all that behind us and look forward to cricket. It's Test-match time. It's day-night Test match time. Adelaide will host its second day-night Test, the first one a win for Australia against trans-Tasman rivals New Zealand. South Africa will pose a different challenge though and Australia now aren't quite what they were back then, personnel and otherwise.

Plenty has gone on in the Australia camp since the Hobart debacle, including but not limited to David Warner's new batting partner. This is another.

Pranay: "Afternoon mate :) So begins a test which despite being a dead rubber could have been a classic but has been terribly marred by off-field issues. However, despite the controversy related to ball tampering, if Australian players don't step up in this match, it will do a great damage to their confidence. World Cricket needs a confident (not over) and competitive (not over) Australia!"
